data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Box lacrosse is played by teams of six on a hockey rink where the ice has been removed or covered by artificial turf , or in an indoor soccer or lacrosse field .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: The enclosed playing area is called a box , in contrast to the open playing field of the traditional game .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: This version of the game was introduced in the 1930s to promote business for hockey arenas , and within several years had nearly supplanted field lacrosse in Canada .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Box lacrosse is played at the highest level by the " Senior A " divisions of the Canadian Lacrosse Association and the National Lacrosse League ( NLL ) .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: The National Lacrosse League employs some minor rule changes from the Canadien Lacrosse Association ( CLA ) rules .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Notably , the games are played during the winter .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: The NLL games consist of four fifteen - minute quarters compared with three periods of twenty minutes each ( similar to ice hockey ) in CLA games ( multiple 15 - minute OT periods for tied games , until whoever scores first ) .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: NLL players may use only sticks with hollow shafts , while CLA permits solid wooden sticks .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: : The goals in box lacrosse are much smaller than field lacrosse , traditionally wide by tall in box , and wide by tall in the NLL.

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Also , the goaltender wears much more protective padding , including a massive chest protector and armguard combination known as " uppers " , large shin guards known as leg pads ( both of which must follow strict measurement guidelines ) , and ice hockey - style masks or lacrosse helmets .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Also , at the professional level , box lacrosse goaltenders often use traditional wooden sticks outside of the NLL , which does not allow wooden sticks .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: This makes Box Lacrosse faster and rougher than the traditional Field Lacrosse .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: The style of the game is quick , accelerated by the close confines of the floor and a shot clock .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: The shot clock requires the attacking team to take a shot on goal within 30 seconds of gaining possession of the ball .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: In addition , players must advance the ball from their own defensive end to the offensive side of the floor within 10 seconds .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Box lacrosse is also a much more physical game .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Since cross checking is legal in box lacrosse , players wear rib pads in addition to the shoulder and elbow pads that field lacrosse players wear .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Box lacrosse players wear a different type of helmet as well , a hockey helmet with a box lacrosse cage .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: For most penalties , the offending player is sent to the penalty box and his team has to play without him ( thus lacking one player ) for a short amount of time .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: Most penalties last for two minutes , unless a five - minute major penalty has been assessed .

data.question: explain box lacrosse
data.answer: What separates box lacrosse ( and ice hockey ) from other sports is that at the top levels of professional and junior lacrosse , a five - minute major penalty is given and the players are not ejected for participating in a fight .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: Vermeer 's painting techniques have long been a source of debate , given their almost photorealistic attention to detail , despite Vermeer having had no formal training , and despite only limited evidence that Vermeer had created any preparatory sketches or traces for his paintings .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: In 2001 , British artist David Hockney published the book " Secret Knowledge : Rediscovering the Lost Techniques of the Old Masters " , in which he argued that Vermeer - among other Renaissance artists including Hans Holbein and Diego Velázquez - used optics , and specifically some combination of curved mirrors , camera obscura and camera lucida , to achieve precise positioning in their compositions .

answer_entities.text: Lost Techniques of the Old Masters

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: This became known as the Hockney – Falco thesis , named after Hockney and Charles M. Falco , another proponent of the theory .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: Working independently , in 2001 British architecture professor Philip Steadman published the book " Vermeer 's Camera : Uncovering the Truth behind the Masterpieces " , which specifically claimed that Vermeer had used a camera obscura to create his paintings .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: Noting that many of Vermeer 's paintings had been painted in the same room , Steadman found six of his paintings that are precisely the right size if they had been painted from inside a camera obscura in the room 's back wall .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: Supporters of these theories have pointed to evidence in some of Vermeer 's paintings , such as the often - discussed sparkling pearly highlights in Vermeer 's paintings , which they argue are the result of the primitive lens of a camera obscura producing halation .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: It was also postulated that a camera obscura was the mechanical cause of the " exaggerated " perspective seen in " Lady at the Virginals with a Gentleman " ( London , Royal Collection ) .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: In 2008 , American entrepreneur and inventor Tim Jenison developed the theory that Vermeer had used a camera obscura along with a " comparator mirror " , which is similar in concept to a camera lucida but much simpler , and allows for easily matching color values .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: He later modified the theory to simply involve a concave mirror and a comparator mirror .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: He spent the next five years testing his theory by attempting to re-create " The Music Lesson " himself using these tools , a process captured in the 2013 documentary film " Tim 's Vermeer " .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: This theory remains disputed .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: Aside from the accurately observed mirror reflection above the lady at the virginals , there is no historical evidence regarding Vermeer 's interest in optics .

data.question: What is the Hockney - Falco postulation ?
data.answer: The detailed inventory of the artist 's belongings drawn up after his death does not include a camera obscura or any similar device .

data.answer: However , in the case of cell cultures from multi-cellular organisms , cell cloning is an arduous task as these cells will not readily grow in standard media .

data.question: What kind of organisms are the most simple to clone ?
data.answer: A useful tissue culture technique used to clone distinct lineages of cell lines involves the use of cloning rings ( cylinders ) .

data.question: What kind of organisms are the most simple to clone ?
data.answer: According to this technique , a single - cell suspension of cells that have been exposed to a mutagenic agent or drug used to drive selection is plated at high dilution to create isolated colonies ; each arising from a single and potentially clonal distinct cell .

data.question: What kind of organisms are the most simple to clone ?
data.answer: At an early growth stage when colonies consist of only a few of cells , sterile polystyrene rings ( cloning rings ) , which have been dipped in grease are placed over an individual colony and a small amount of trypsin is added .

data.question: What kind of organisms are the most simple to clone ?
data.answer: Cloned cells are collected from inside the ring and transferred to a new vessel for further growth .

data.question: What parts of David are very large ?

data.question: What parts of David are very large ?

data.question: What parts of David are very large ?
data.answer: Vasari described it as " certainly a miracle that of Michelangelo , to restore to life one who was dead , " and then listed all of the largest and most grand of the ancient statues that he had ever seen , concluding that Michelangelo 's work surpassed " all ancient and modern statues , whether Greek or Latin , that have ever existed . "

data.question: What parts of David are very large ?

data.question: What parts of David are very large ?

data.question: What parts of David are very large ?
data.answer: Donatello 's bronze " David , " made for the Medici family , perhaps 1440 , had been appropriated by the Signoria in 1494 , when the Medici were exiled from Florence , and the statue was installed in the courtyard of the Palazzo della Signoria , where it stood for the Republican government of the city .

data.question: What parts of David are very large ?

data.question: What parts of David are very large ?

data.answer: Reflection nebulae themselves do not emit significant amounts of visible light , but are near stars and reflect light from them .

data.answer: Although these nebulae have different visibility at optical wavelengths , they are all bright sources of infrared emission , chiefly from dust within the nebulae .

data.question: What does the survival of a living organism depend on ?
data.answer: The survival of a living organism depends on the continuous input of energy .

data.question: What does the survival of a living organism depend on ?
data.answer: Chemical reactions that are responsible for its structure and function are tuned to extract energy from substances that act as its food and transform them to help form new cells and sustain them .

data.answer: The organisms responsible for the introduction of energy into an ecosystem are known as producers or autotrophs .

data.question: What does the survival of a living organism depend on ?
data.answer: Nearly all of these organisms originally draw energy from the sun .

data.question: What does the survival of a living organism depend on ?
data.answer: Plants and other phototrophs use solar energy via a process known as photosynthesis to convert raw materials into organic molecules , such as ATP , whose bonds can be broken to release energy .

data.question: What does the survival of a living organism depend on ?
data.answer: A few ecosystems , however , depend entirely on energy extracted by chemotrophs from methane , sulfides , or other non-luminal energy sources .

data.question: What does the survival of a living organism depend on ?
data.answer: Some of the captured energy is used to produce biomass to sustain life and provide energy for growth and development .

data.question: What does the survival of a living organism depend on ?
data.answer: The majority of the rest of this energy is lost as heat and waste molecules .

data.question: What does the survival of a living organism depend on ?
data.answer: The most important processes for converting the energy trapped in chemical substances into energy useful to sustain life are metabolism and cellular respiration .

data.answer: They reached broadly similar conclusions : the regulations on the number of lifeboats that ships had to carry were out of date and inadequate ; Captain Smith had failed to take proper heed of ice warnings ; the lifeboats had not been properly filled or crewed ; and the collision was the direct result of steaming into a danger area at too high a speed .

"

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: Cheese is an ancient food whose origins predate recorded history .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: There is no conclusive evidence indicating where cheesemaking originated , either in Europe , Central Asia or the Middle East , but the practice had spread within Europe prior to Roman times and , according to Pliny the Elder , had become a sophisticated enterprise by the time the Roman Empire came into being .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: The earliest evidence of cheese - making in the archaeological record dates back to 5,500 BCE , in what is now Kujawy , Poland , where strainers with milk fats molecules have been found .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: Earliest proposed dates for the origin of cheesemaking range from around 8000 BCE , when sheep were first domesticated .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: Since animal skins and inflated internal organs have , since ancient times , provided storage vessels for a range of foodstuffs , it is probable that the process of cheese making was discovered accidentally by storing milk in a container made from the stomach of an animal , resulting in the milk being turned to curd and whey by the rennet from the stomach .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: There is a legend – with variations – about the discovery of cheese by an Arab trader who used this method of storing milk .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: Cheesemaking may have begun independently of this by the pressing and salting of curdled milk to preserve it .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: Observation that the effect of making milk in an animal stomach gave more solid and better - textured curds may have led to the deliberate addition of rennet .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: Early archeological evidence of Egyptian cheese has been found in Egyptian tomb murals , dating to about 2000 BCE .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: The earliest cheeses were likely to have been quite sour and salty , similar in texture to rustic cottage cheese or feta , a crumbly , flavorful Greek cheese .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: Cheese produced in Europe , where climates are cooler than the Middle East , required less salt for preservation .

data.question: How was cheese making discovered ?
data.answer: With less salt and acidity , the cheese became a suitable environment for useful microbes and molds , giving aged cheeses their respective flavors .

data.answer: In general terms , gravitational waves are radiated by objects whose motion involves acceleration , provided that the motion is not perfectly spherically symmetric ( like an expanding or contracting sphere ) or cylindrically symmetric ( like a spinning disk or sphere ) .

data.question: Which way must a dumbbell fall to radiate gravitational waves ?

data.answer: The heavier the dumbbell , and the faster it tumbles , the greater is the gravitational radiation it will give off .

data.question: Which way must a dumbbell fall to radiate gravitational waves ?

data.answer: Some more detailed examples :

data.question: Which way must a dumbbell fall to radiate gravitational waves ?
data.answer: A supernova will radiate except in the unlikely event that the explosion is perfectly symmetric .

data.question: Which way must a dumbbell fall to radiate gravitational waves ?

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: Some bacteria also transfer genetic material between cells .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: This can occur in three main ways .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: First , bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment , in a process called transformation .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: Genes can also be transferred by the process of transduction , when the integration of a bacteriophage introduces foreign DNA into the chromosome .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: The third method of gene transfer is conjugation , whereby DNA is transferred through direct cell contact .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: Transduction of bacterial genes by bacteriophage appears to be a consequence of infrequent errors during intracellular assembly of virus particles , rather than a bacterial adaptation .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: Conjugation , in the much - studied E. coli system is determined by plasmid genes , and is an adaptation for transferring copies of the plasmid from one bacterial host to another .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: It is seldom that a conjugative plasmid integrates into the host bacterial chromosome , and subsequently transfers part of the host bacterial DNA to another bacterium .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: Plasmid - mediated transfer of host bacterial DNA also appears to be an accidental process rather than a bacterial adaptation .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: Transformation , unlike transduction or conjugation , depends on numerous bacterial gene products that specifically interact to perform this complex process , and thus transformation is clearly a bacterial adaptation for DNA transfer .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: In order for a bacterium to bind , take up and recombine donor DNA into its own chromosome , it must first enter a special physiological state termed competence ( see Natural competence ) .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: In " Bacillus subtilis " about 40 genes are required for the development of competence .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: The length of DNA transferred during " B. subtilis " transformation can be between a third of a chromosome up to the whole chromosome .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: Transformation appears to be common among bacterial species , and thus far at least 60 species are known to have the natural ability to become competent for transformation .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions , and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: In ordinary circumstances , transduction , conjugation , and transformation involve transfer of DNA between individual bacteria of the same species , but occasionally transfer may occur between individuals of different bacterial species and this may have significant consequences , such as the transfer of antibiotic resistance .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: In such cases , gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions .

data.question: Gene transfer is important for what reasons ?
data.answer: Gene transfer is particularly important in antibiotic resistance as it allows the rapid transfer of resistance genes between different pathogens .

data.answer: Both are depicted as being inferior to Zhuge Liang in every respect .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: Some bacteria also transfer genetic material between cells .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: This can occur in three main ways .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: First , bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment , in a process called transformation .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: Genes can also be transferred by the process of transduction , when the integration of a bacteriophage introduces foreign DNA into the chromosome .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: The third method of gene transfer is conjugation , whereby DNA is transferred through direct cell contact .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: Transduction of bacterial genes by bacteriophage appears to be a consequence of infrequent errors during intracellular assembly of virus particles , rather than a bacterial adaptation .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: Conjugation , in the much - studied E. coli system is determined by plasmid genes , and is an adaptation for transferring copies of the plasmid from one bacterial host to another .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: It is seldom that a conjugative plasmid integrates into the host bacterial chromosome , and subsequently transfers part of the host bacterial DNA to another bacterium .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: Plasmid - mediated transfer of host bacterial DNA also appears to be an accidental process rather than a bacterial adaptation .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: Transformation , unlike transduction or conjugation , depends on numerous bacterial gene products that specifically interact to perform this complex process , and thus transformation is clearly a bacterial adaptation for DNA transfer .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: In order for a bacterium to bind , take up and recombine donor DNA into its own chromosome , it must first enter a special physiological state termed competence ( see Natural competence ) .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: In " Bacillus subtilis " about 40 genes are required for the development of competence .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: The length of DNA transferred during " B. subtilis " transformation can be between a third of a chromosome up to the whole chromosome .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: Transformation appears to be common among bacterial species , and thus far at least 60 species are known to have the natural ability to become competent for transformation .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions , and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: In ordinary circumstances , transduction , conjugation , and transformation involve transfer of DNA between individual bacteria of the same species , but occasionally transfer may occur between individuals of different bacterial species and this may have significant consequences , such as the transfer of antibiotic resistance .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: In such cases , gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions .

data.question: What are some possible ways bacteria can spread between cells ?
data.answer: Gene transfer is particularly important in antibiotic resistance as it allows the rapid transfer of resistance genes between different pathogens .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Research over the past few decades has shown that the nutrients and minerals in seafood can make improvements in brain development and reproduction and has highlighted the role for seafood in the functions of the human body .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Doctors have known of strong links between fish and healthy hearts ever since they noticed that fish - eating Inuit populations in the Arctic had low levels of heart disease .

data.answer: Omega-3 fats also have natural built - in anti-oxidants , which are thought to stop the thickening and damaging of artery walls .

data.answer: Recent studies suggest that older people can boost their brain power by eating more oily fish , what with regular consumers being able to remember better and think faster than those who do n't consume at all .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Other research has also suggested that adding more DHA to the diet of children with attention - deficit hyperactivity disorder can reduce their behavioural problems and improve their reading skills , while there have also been links suggested between DHA and better concentration .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Separate studies have suggested that older people who eat fish at least once a week could also have a lower chance of developing dementia and Alzheimer 's disease .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Including fish as a regular part of a balanced diet has been shown to help the symptoms of rheumatoid arthritis – a painful condition that causes joints to swell up , reducing strength and mobility .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Studies also show that sufferers feel less stiff and sore in the morning if they keep their fish oil intake topped up .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Recent research has also found a link between Omega-3 fats and a slowing down in the wearing of cartilage that leads to osteoarthritis , opening the door for more research into whether eating more fish could help prevent the disease .

data.answer: Fish is high in minerals such as zinc , iodine and selenium , which keep the body running smoothly .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Iodine is essential for the thyroid gland , which controls growth and metabolism , while selenium is used to make enzymes that protect cell walls from cancer - causing free radicals , and helps prevent DNA damage caused by radiation and some chemicals .

data.question: How do seniors benefit from eating oily fish ?
data.answer: Fish is also a source of vitamin A , which is needed for healthy skin and eyes , and vitamin D , which is needed to help the body absorb calcium to strengthen teeth and bones .

data.question: Why is there a stair - shaped line between metals and nonmetals on the periodic table ?
data.answer: The lower the values of ionization energy , electronegativity and electron affinity , the more metallic character the element has .

data.question: Why is there a stair - shaped line between metals and nonmetals on the periodic table ?
data.answer: Conversely , nonmetallic character increases with higher values of these properties .

data.question: Why is there a stair - shaped line between metals and nonmetals on the periodic table ?
data.answer: Given the periodic trends of these three properties , metallic character tends to decrease going across a period ( or row ) and , with some irregularities ( mostly ) due to poor screening of the nucleus by d and f electrons , and relativistic effects , tends to increase going down a group ( or column or family ) .

data.question: Why is there a stair - shaped line between metals and nonmetals on the periodic table ?
data.answer: Thus , the most metallic elements ( such as caesium and francium ) are found at the bottom left of traditional periodic tables and the most nonmetallic elements ( oxygen , fluorine , chlorine ) at the top right .

data.question: Why is there a stair - shaped line between metals and nonmetals on the periodic table ?
data.answer: The combination of horizontal and vertical trends in metallic character explains the stair - shaped dividing line between metals and nonmetals found on some periodic tables , and the practice of sometimes categorizing several elements adjacent to that line , or elements adjacent to those elements , as metalloids .

data.answer: Given the periodic trends of these three properties , metallic character tends to decrease going across a period ( or row ) and , with some irregularities ( mostly ) due to poor screening of the nucleus by d and f electrons , and relativistic effects , tends to increase going down a group ( or column or family ) .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?
data.answer: In 1915 the reason for nuclear charge being quantized in units of Z , which were now recognized to be the same as the element number , was not understood .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?
data.answer: An old idea called Prout 's hypothesis had postulated that the elements were all made of residues ( or " protyles " ) of the lightest element hydrogen , which in the Bohr - Rutherford model had a single electron and a nuclear charge of one .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?
data.answer: However , as early as 1907 Rutherford and Thomas Royds had shown that alpha particles , which had a charge of +2 , were the nuclei of helium atoms , which had a mass four times that of hydrogen , not two times .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?
data.answer: If Prout 's hypothesis were true , something had to be neutralizing some of the charge of the hydrogen nuclei present in the nuclei of heavier atoms .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?
data.answer: In 1917 Rutherford succeeded in generating hydrogen nuclei from a nuclear reaction between alpha particles and nitrogen gas , and believed he had proven Prout 's law .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?
data.answer: He called the new heavy nuclear particles protons in 1920 ( alternate names being proutons and protyles ) .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?
data.answer: It had been immediately apparent from the work of Moseley that the nuclei of heavy atoms have more than twice as much mass as would be expected from their being made of hydrogen nuclei , and thus there was required a hypothesis for the neutralization of the extra protons presumed present in all heavy nuclei .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?
data.answer: A helium nucleus was presumed to be composed of four protons plus two " nuclear electrons " ( electrons bound inside the nucleus ) to cancel two of the charges .

data.question: What is the name of the scientist that generated Hydrogen nuclei from reactions between nitrogen and alpha particles ?

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Western riding evolved from the cattle - working and warfare traditions brought to the Americas by the Spanish Conquistadors , and both equipment and riding style evolved to meet the working needs of the cowboy on ranches in the American West .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Though the differences between English and Western riding appear dramatic , there are more similarities than most people think .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Both styles require riders to have a solid seat , with the hips and shoulders balanced over the feet , with hands independent of the seat so as to avoid disturbing the balance of the horse and interfering with its performance .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: The most noticeable feature of western style riding is in the saddle , which has a substantial tree that provides greater support to horse and rider when working long hours in the saddle .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: The western saddle features a prominent pommel topped by a horn ( a knob used for dallying a lariat after roping an animal ) , a deep seat and a high cantle .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: The stirrups are wider and the saddle has rings and ties that allow objects to be attached to the saddle .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Western horses are asked to perform with a loose rein , controlled by one hand .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: The standard western bridle lacks a noseband and usually consists of a single set of reins attached to a curb bit that has somewhat longer and looser shanks than the curb of an English Weymouth bridle or a pelham bit .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Two styles of Western reins developed : The long split reins of the Texas tradition , which are completely separated , or the closed - end " Romal " reins of the California tradition , which have a long single attachment on the ends that can be used as a quirt .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Modern rodeo competitors in timed events sometimes use a closed rein without a " romal " .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Western riders wear a long - sleeved shirt , denim jeans , boots , and a wide - brimmed cowboy hat .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Cowboy boots , which have pointed toes and higher heels than a traditional riding boot , are designed to prevent the rider 's foot from slipping through the stirrup during a fall , preventing the rider from being dragged—most western saddles have no safety bars for the leathers or automatic stirrup release mechanism .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: A rider may wear protective leather leggings called chaps .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Clean , well - fitting work clothing is the usual outfit seen in rodeo , cutting and reining competitions , especially for men , though sometimes both men and women wear brighter colors or finer fabrics for competition than for work .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Show events such as Western pleasure use much flashier equipment , unlike the English traditions where clothing and tack is quiet and unobtrusive .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Saddles , bits and bridles are ornamented with substantial amounts of silver .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: The rider may add a jacket or vest , and women 's clothing in particular features vivid colors and even , depending on current fads , rhinestones or sequins .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Western horses are asked to have a brisk , ground - covering walk , but a slow , relaxed jog trot that allows the rider to sit the saddle and not post .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: The Western version of the canter is called a " lope " and while collected and balanced , is expected to be slow and relaxed .

data.question: How are cowboy boots designed ?
data.answer: Working western horses seldom use a sustained hand gallop , but must be able to accelerate quickly to high speed when chasing cattle or competing in rodeo speed events , must be able to stop quickly from a dead run and " turn on a dime . "

data.answer: The paintings in the Vatican by Michelangelo and Raphael are said by some scholars such as Stephen Freedberg to represent the culmination of High Renaissance style in painting , because of the ambitious scale of these works , coupled with the complexity of their composition , closely observed human figures , and pointed iconographic and decorative references to classical antiquity , can be viewed as emblematic of the High Renaissance .

data.question: Who were the most well - known painters during the High Renaissance period ?

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: Monetarists , including Milton Friedman , argue that the Great Depression was mainly caused by monetary contraction , the consequence of poor policy - making by the American Federal Reserve System and continued crisis in the banking system .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: In this view , the Federal Reserve , by not acting , allowed the money supply as measured by the M2 to shrink by one - third from 1929–1933 , thereby transforming a normal recession into the Great Depression .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: Friedman argued that the downward turn in the economy , starting with the stock market crash , would have been just another recession .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: The Federal Reserve allowed some large public bank failures – particularly that of the New York Bank of the United States – which produced panic and widespread runs on local banks , and the Federal Reserve sat idly by while banks collapsed .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: He claimed that , if the Fed had provided emergency lending to these key banks , or simply bought government bonds on the open market to provide liquidity and increase the quantity of money after the key banks fell , all the rest of the banks would not have fallen after the large ones did , and the money supply would not have fallen as far and as fast as it did .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: With significantly less money to go around , businessmen could not get new loans and could not even get their old loans renewed , forcing many to stop investing .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: This interpretation blames the Federal Reserve for inaction , especially the New York branch .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: One reason why the Federal Reserve did not act to limit the decline of the money supply was regulation .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: At that time , the amount of credit the Federal Reserve could issue was limited by the Federal Reserve Act , which required 40 % gold backing of Federal Reserve Notes issued .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: By the late 1920s , the Federal Reserve had almost hit the limit of allowable credit that could be backed by the gold in its possession .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: This credit was in the form of Federal Reserve demand notes .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: A " promise of gold " is not as good as " gold in the hand " , particularly when they only had enough gold to cover 40 % of the Federal Reserve Notes outstanding .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: During the bank panics a portion of those demand notes were redeemed for Federal Reserve gold .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?
data.answer: Since the Federal Reserve had hit its limit on allowable credit , any reduction in gold in its vaults had to be accompanied by a greater reduction in credit .

data.question: What was the cause of the Great Depression from the viewpoint of Monetarists ?

data.question: Who was the first man in space ?

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: Because a black hole has only a few internal parameters , most of the information about the matter that went into forming the black hole is lost .

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: Regardless of the type of matter which goes into a black hole , it appears that only information concerning the total mass , charge , and angular momentum are conserved .

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: As long as black holes were thought to persist forever this information loss is not that problematic , as the information can be thought of as existing inside the black hole , inaccessible from the outside .

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: However , black holes slowly evaporate by emitting Hawking radiation .

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: This radiation does not appear to carry any additional information about the matter that formed the black hole , meaning that this information appears to be gone forever .

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: The question whether information is truly lost in black holes ( the black hole information paradox ) has divided the theoretical physics community ( see Thorne – Hawking – Preskill bet ) .

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: In quantum mechanics , loss of information corresponds to the violation of vital property called unitarity , which has to do with the conservation of probability .

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: It has been argued that loss of unitarity would also imply violation of conservation of energy .

data.question: What cause black holes to slowly evaporate ?
data.answer: Over recent years evidence has been building that indeed information and unitarity are preserved in a full quantum gravitational treatment of the problem .

data.answer: In order to determine whether two proteins are related , or in other words to decide whether they are homologous or not , scientists use sequence - comparison methods .

data.answer: The relevance of finding homologies among proteins goes beyond forming an evolutionary pattern of protein families .

data.question: What are proteins ?

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: The planning of radiation therapy treatment has been revolutionized by the ability to delineate tumors and adjacent normal structures in three dimensions using specialized CT and / or MRI scanners and planning software .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: Virtual simulation , the most basic form of planning , allows more accurate placement of radiation beams than is possible using conventional X-rays , where soft - tissue structures are often difficult to assess and normal tissues difficult to protect .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: An enhancement of virtual simulation is 3 - dimensional conformal radiation therapy ( 3DCRT ) , in which the profile of each radiation beam is shaped to fit the profile of the target from a beam 's eye view ( BEV ) using a multileaf collimator ( MLC ) and a variable number of beams .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: When the treatment volume conforms to the shape of the tumor , the relative toxicity of radiation to the surrounding normal tissues is reduced , allowing a higher dose of radiation to be delivered to the tumor than conventional techniques would allow .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: Intensity - modulated radiation therapy ( IMRT ) is an advanced type of high - precision radiation that is the next generation of 3DCRT .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: IMRT also improves the ability to conform the treatment volume to concave tumor shapes , for example when the tumor is wrapped around a vulnerable structure such as the spinal cord or a major organ or blood vessel .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: Computer - controlled x-ray accelerators distribute precise radiation doses to malignant tumors or specific areas within the tumor .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: The radiation dose intensity is elevated near the gross tumor volume while radiation among the neighboring normal tissue is decreased or avoided completely .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?
data.answer: The customized radiation dose is intended to maximize tumor dose while simultaneously protecting the surrounding normal tissue .

data.question: How is IMRT technology limited ?

data.question: Who designed the Statue of Liberty ?
data.answer: The Statue of Liberty ( Liberty Enlightening the World ; French : " La Liberté éclairant le monde " ) is a colossal neoclassical sculpture on Liberty Island in the middle of New York Harbor , in Manhattan , New York City .

data.question: Who designed the Statue of Liberty ?
data.answer: The statue , designed by Frédéric Auguste Bartholdi and dedicated on October 28 , 1886 , was a gift to the United States from the people of France .

data.question: Who designed the Statue of Liberty ?
data.answer: The statue is of a robed female figure representing Libertas , the Roman goddess of freedom , who bears a torch and a " tabula ansata " ( a tablet evoking the law ) upon which is inscribed the date of the American Declaration of Independence , July 4 , 1776 .

data.question: Who designed the Statue of Liberty ?
data.answer: A broken chain lies at her feet .

data.answer: Bartholdi was inspired by French law professor and politician Édouard René de Laboulaye , who is said to have commented in 1865 that any monument raised to American independence would properly be a joint project of the French and American peoples .

data.question: Who designed the Statue of Liberty ?
data.answer: Due to the troubled political situation in France , work on the statue did not commence until the early 1870s .

data.question: Who designed the Statue of Liberty ?

data.question: Who are the best - known painters of the High Renaissance ?
data.answer: Since the late eighteenth century , the High Renaissance has been taken to refer to a short ( c. 30 - year ) period of exceptional artistic production in the Italian states , principally Rome , capital of the Papal States , under Pope Julius II .

data.question: Who are the best - known painters of the High Renaissance ?
data.answer: Assertions about where and when the period begins and ends vary , but in general the best - known exponents of painting of the High Renaissance , include Leonardo da Vinci , early Michelangelo and Raphael .

data.question: Who are the best - known painters of the High Renaissance ?
data.answer: Extending the general rubric of Renaissance culture , the visual arts of the High Renaissance were marked by a renewed emphasis upon the classical tradition , the expansion of networks of patronage , and a gradual attenuation of figural forms into the style later termed Mannerism .

data.question: Who are the best - known painters of the High Renaissance ?
data.answer: The paintings in the Vatican by Michelangelo and Raphael are said by some scholars such as Stephen Freedberg to represent the culmination of High Renaissance style in painting , because of the ambitious scale of these works , coupled with the complexity of their composition , closely observed human figures , and pointed iconographic and decorative references to classical antiquity , can be viewed as emblematic of the High Renaissance .

data.question: Who are the best - known painters of the High Renaissance ?
data.answer: In more recent years , art historians have characterised the High Renaissance as a movement as opposed to a period , one amongst several different experimental attitudes towards art in the late fifteenth and early sixteenth century .

data.question: Who are the best - known painters of the High Renaissance ?
data.answer: This movement is variously characterised as conservative ; as reflecting new attitudes towards beauty ; a deliberate process of synthesising eclectic models , linked to fashions in literary culture ; and reflecting new preoccupations with interpretation and meaning .
